  "prompt": "What is thermal inversion?",
  "response": "Thermal inversion, also known as temperature inversion, is a meteorological phenomenon where the normal temperature gradient of the atmosphere is reversed. Typically, air temperature decreases with altitude, meaning it is cooler at higher elevations. During a thermal inversion, however, a layer of warmer air sits above a layer of cooler air near the ground. This inversion layer can trap pollutants and particulate matter, leading to higher concentrations of smog and poor air quality.\n\nThermal inversions commonly occur in valleys or areas surrounded by mountains, especially during the winter months when nights are long and strong radiative cooling can occur. They are often associated with calm weather conditions, as strong winds can disrupt the inversion layer. The presence of a thermal inversion can significantly affect local climate and pollution levels, making it an important factor in environmental and public health studies.",
